            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How the Illinois income tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                Illinois is a <strong>flat-tax state</strong>: most individual
                taxpayers pay the same percentage of their Illinois taxable
                income, regardless of income level. However, your
                <strong>effective tax rate</strong> can be lower once exemptions
                and credits are applied.
              </p>
              <p>
                This calculator is designed to be transparent. It shows each
                step: starting from your Illinois taxable income, subtracting
                personal exemptions, applying the flat rate, subtracting
                credits, and optionally adding local income tax.
              </p>

              <h3>Step 1 – Start with Illinois taxable income</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator begins with the value you enter as
                <strong>Illinois taxable income</strong>. In practice, this is
                usually your federal adjusted gross income (AGI) plus or minus
                Illinois additions and subtractions.
              </p>
              <p>
                If you do not know your exact Illinois taxable income yet, you
                can approximate it with:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Approximate IL taxable income</strong> ≈ Gross income
                  − pre‑tax deductions − adjustments
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Step 2 – Subtract personal exemptions</h3>
              <p>
                Illinois allows a <strong>personal exemption amount</strong> for
                you, your spouse (if applicable), and qualifying dependents. For
                each exemption, the calculator subtracts a fixed dollar amount
                from your Illinois taxable income:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Exemption total</strong> = Number of exemptions ×
                  Exemption amount per person
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Taxable base after exemptions</strong> = IL taxable
                  income − Exemption total
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                If the result is negative, the calculator treats it as zero (you
                cannot have negative taxable income for this step).
              </p>

              <h3>Step 3 – Apply the Illinois flat tax rate</h3>
              <p>
                After exemptions, the calculator applies the
                <strong>Illinois flat income tax rate</strong> for the selected
                tax year:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Illinois state tax before credits</strong> = Taxable
                  base after exemptions × IL flat tax rate
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Step 4 – Subtract Illinois tax credits</h3>
              <p>
                Illinois offers several
                <strong>non‑refundable credits</strong> (for example, the
                property tax credit or education expense credit). These reduce
                your Illinois tax liability dollar‑for‑dollar, but generally
                cannot reduce it below zero.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Illinois state tax after credits</strong> = max(0,
                  State tax before credits − IL credits)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Step 5 – Optional local income tax</h3>
              <p>
                Some Illinois localities or special districts may impose
                additional income or earnings taxes. To model this, the
                calculator lets you:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Toggle local income tax on or off.</li>
                <li>Choose a <strong>local tax rate</strong> (percentage).</li>
                <li>
                  Choose whether the local tax applies to
                  <strong>Illinois taxable income</strong> or to your
                  <strong>gross income</strong>.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Local tax</strong> = Local tax base × Local tax rate
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Total IL + local tax</strong> = Illinois state tax
                  after credits + Local tax
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Step 6 – Effective tax rate and take‑home pay</h3>
              <p>To help you compare your tax burden, the calculator shows:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Illinois flat tax rate</strong> (statutory rate).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Effective Illinois tax rate</strong> = State tax after
                  credits ÷ IL taxable income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Estimated take‑home pay after Illinois tax</strong> =
                  IL taxable income − Total IL + local tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If you enter an estimate of your
                  <strong>federal income tax</strong>, it also shows
                  <strong>take‑home pay after federal + Illinois</strong>.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Illinois income tax formula (simplified)</h2>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>1.</strong> Exemption total = Exemptions × Exemption
                  amount
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>2.</strong> IL taxable base = max(0, IL taxable income
                  − Exemption total)
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>3.</strong> State tax before credits = IL taxable base
                  × IL flat tax rate
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>4.</strong> State tax after credits = max(0, State tax
                  before credits − IL credits)
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>5.</strong> Local tax (optional) = Local base × Local
                  rate
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>6.</strong> Total IL + local tax = State tax after
                  credits + Local tax
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>7.</strong> Effective IL tax rate = State tax after
                  credits ÷ IL taxable income
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator performs these steps automatically and updates
                the results instantly when you click
                <strong>“Calculate Illinois tax”</strong>.
              </p>

              <h2>Example: Illinois income tax for a single filer</h2>
              <p>Suppose:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Filing status: Single</li>
                <li>Illinois taxable income: $60,000</li>
                <li>Personal exemptions: 1</li>
                <li>Illinois credits: $0</li>
                <li>No local income tax</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Then, roughly:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>Exemption total = 1 × exemption amount.</li>
                <li>IL taxable base = $60,000 − exemption total.</li>
                <li>State tax before credits = IL taxable base × flat rate.</li>
                <li>
                  State tax after credits = same as before credits (no credits).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Effective IL tax rate = State tax after credits ÷ $60,000.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                The calculator will show the exact dollar amounts based on the
                current year’s rate and exemption values.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This tool focuses on
                  <strong>Illinois state income tax</strong> and optional local
                  income tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does not compute every possible Illinois credit, deduction,
                  or special rule.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does not prepare or file your Illinois or federal tax
                  return.
                </li>
                <li>
                  For official guidance, always refer to the
                  <a
                    href="https://tax.illinois.gov/"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                    >Illinois Department of Revenue</a
                  >
                  and the IRS.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-8">
